 ) - this is a model of subjective uncertainty.
 Thus if one were to view PnL targets as utility under risk, it follows
 that the perception risk in financial securities varies across the several
 business units at a typical investment bank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market risk associated with an equities portfolio is usually detached
 from the credit risk - which analyses the factors undermining the portfolio
 with a set of inputs different from what market risk may be interested
 in.
 As such each security is meant to have some credit risk - i.e.
 a (usually low) probability of losing a high amount and the probability
 that it would under-perform i.e.
 a relatively high probability of loss in value.
 These are however hardly accumulated as a combined utility under risk at
 a financial institution.
 More particularly, the probabilities inferred from historical volatility
 used for market risk may be disconnected with the default probabilities
 that the bank may obtain from .
 A fragmented view of risk is evident as every desk measures resorts to
 managing risk it in its own way - driven largely by the time-horizon of
 the investment, the holding period of the particular type of products and
 the market data relevant to the security.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a separation is in everyone's interest since the institution necessarily
 participates in the markets for credit products and rates/equities products
 to ensure a reliable distribution of risk prevails.
 However, since markets are not always inefficient, the bank must also engage
 in the opportunities where risk is undervalued or overvalued.
 Such opportunities need not be indicated to the market except through investmen
ts.
 The reason why the bank does not engage in a transparent methodical way
 of having such a unified risk approach is because i) the predictive power
 of the risk that is based on the particular markets is much higher - therefore
 the returns from a possible integration of risk do not translate into anything
 monetary ii) a market for such an information doesn't exist (a part of
 it is explained by Diamond Rajan perspective of illiquid perspective 
