\begin_layout Standard
From a central banking perspective, a higher level risk view - or the bias
 parameters - could thus be useful in two ways.
 First because an incentive-based model of why such trends develop could
 be provided.
 While it is true that the information is forced to flow to the market instead
 of staying within the bank - but latter may be less likely to happen.
 It it only by understanding of the incentives that we would be able to
 understand if there communication within the bank can allow such an exchange
 to happen - meaning that such flow is implicit.
 Second, because banks are also engaging in such activities as Machine Learning
 methods to find opportunities (while reportedly saving costs 
