 future, the hurdles required in regularising such automation would also
 complicate the presentation of model risk.
 .
 An information-theory model of how such information could flow within the
 division at a bank could help policy rein in possible extreme risk-taking.
 An information hierarchy with a behavioural model where agents optimised
 a probability-weighted utility function as they observe a cross-section
 of market is therefore planned to be used for this study.
 With the use of Bayesian econometrics, one could evaluate the the banks
 own bias eventually in taking a risk - thus parametrising the risk that
 could be of use to policy.
 
